Including images

knitr::include_graphics(
  here::here( #Dit stelt de workingdirectory in op de folder waarin dit RMarkdown bestand staat, ./DSFB2/workflows_lessen
    "images",
    "afbeelding_naam.png"
  )
)
#"Setting the dpi option in the code chunk controls the size of the image displayed in the rendered output"

          "#F0E442", "#0072B2", "#D55E00", "#CC79A7")

library(palmerpenguins)

mass_hist <- ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = body_mass_g)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = species),
                 alpha = 0.8,
                 position = "identity") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("darkorange","purple","cyan4")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Body mass (g)",
       y = "Frequency",
       title = "Penguin body mass")

mass_hist + scale_fill_manual(values = cbp1)

library(RColorBrewer)

plot <- ggplot(iris, aes(Species, Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = Species)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

#Voor een boxplot (fill):

Exercise 5.1

#New packages
install.packages("hrbrthemes")
# Libraries
library(tidyverse)
library(hrbrthemes)
library(viridis)

# create a dataset
data <- data.frame(
  name=c( rep("A",500), rep("B",500), rep("B",500), rep("C",20), rep('D', 100)  ),
  value=c( rnorm(500, 10, 5), rnorm(500, 13, 1), rnorm(500, 18, 1), rnorm(20, 25, 4), rnorm(100, 12, 1) )
)

# Plot
bp <- data %>%
  ggplot( aes(x=name, y=value, fill=name)) +
    geom_boxplot() +
    scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE, alpha=0.6) +
    geom_jitter(color="black", size=0.4, alpha=0.9) +
    theme_ipsum() +
    theme(
      legend.position="none",
      plot.title = element_text(size=11)
    ) +
    ggtitle("A boxplot with jitter") +
    xlab("")

# Zelf toegevoegd:
bp + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Dark2")

Complexere tabellen maken met de kableExtra package:

library(kableExtra)

# take just a few columns and rows for demonstration purposes
data_for_table <- mtcars[1:5, 1:6]

kbl(data_for_table) %>% kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped", full_width = F, position = "left") #Geen volledige grote en centreer naar links

If you know a chunk will not need to change as other parts of the document are knitted, you can cache a chunk that contains a potentially long-running or slow command: cache=TRUE in chunk header.

CSS

CSS is a simple mechanism for adding style to Web documents.

Doorzichtig-rode achtergrond voor code, doorzichtig-gele achtergrond voor output:

mtcars[1:5, "mpg"]
## [1] 21.0 21.0 22.8 21.4 18.7

Eigen style (watch-out) maken:

en toepassen op een chunk:

mtcars[1:5, "mpg"]
## [1] 21.0 21.0 22.8 21.4 18.7

Defining all your styling stuff within your RMarkdown gets messy, put them in a separate .css file in the same folder as the .Rmd. For instance the .css contains:

.bordershere { border-style: solid; border-width: 5px; border-color: purple; }

Link the custom style to the .Rmd in the YAML header: output: html_document: css: my-style-sheet.css

You can also use html

tags to apply a css style to part of your .Rmd:

text in your .Rmd </div
